#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:49
msgid "When testing or running in dev mode Quarkus can even provide you with a zero config database out of the box, a feature we refer to as Dev Services. Depending on your database type you may need docker installed in order to use this feature. Dev Services is supported for the following open source databases:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:51
msgid "Postgresql (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:52
msgid "MySQL (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:53
msgid "MariaDB (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:54
msgid "H2 (in-process)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:55
msgid "Apache Derby (in-process)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:56
msgid "DB2 (container) (requires license acceptance)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:57
msgid "MSSQL (container) (requires license acceptance)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:62
msgid "If you want to use Dev Services then all you need to do is include the relevant extension for the type of database you want (either reactive or JDBC, or both), and don't configure a database URL, username and password, Quarkus will provide the database and you can just start coding without worrying about config."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/2.2/guides/datasource.adoc:68
